  

<h2 id="dedicated-read-it-later-apps-are-nice-not-necessary">Dedicated Read-It-Later apps are nice, not necessary</h2>
<p>The links you save today might be a mystery tomorrow. Time to change that.</p>
<p>Thirty seconds can mean the difference between one more link being lost to the black hole of ambiguity, and having useful resources at your fingertips.</p>
<h2 id="case-study-the-macquarie-banking-app">Case study: the MacQuarie banking app</h2>
<p>The award winning Australian MacQuarie banking app is easily the best finance-related app on my phone. It‚Äôs the only one with dark mode (a big plus), but what I especially appreciate is the<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>I want to‚Ä¶‚Äù drop down list that is front and centre after you click on an account.</p>
<!--![iPhone screenshot showing a dropdown list for actions to take on a bank account. Each option begins with a verb, such as Pay from this account, Transfer between accounts, View account statements.](../_Files/PTPL-165-macquarie.png)-->
<p>Each item on the list begins with a verb, eg.</p>
<p>I want to‚Ä¶</p>
<ul>
<li>Pay from this account</li>
<li>Transfer between accounts</li>
<li>View account statements</li>
</ul>
<p>Each time I open the app I relax, knowing I don‚Äôt have to remember which action is hiding behind which menu. All I have to do is to think,<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>I want to‚Ä¶‚Äù and the app provides the rest. The same information exists in my other banking apps as a list under a menu, but somehow it‚Äôs not as welcoming, not as accessible. Those verbs are powerful!</p>
<p>This is a good lesson in <span class="small-caps">UX</span> design, and it‚Äôs one you can apply to the links you save for future reading. You want to feel this same level of relaxation and confidence when<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>later‚Äù finally comes.</p>
<h2 id="know-your-why">Know your why!</h2>
<p>If you can‚Äôt immediately tell why you saved an article or a link, your saved links and Read-It-Later system is a list of distractions rather than a useful resource. The why behind today‚Äôs links is still clear, but next month it might not be quite so apparent.</p>
<p><strong>You need a way to communicate with the you of tomorrow that won‚Äôt overly tax the you of today.</strong></p>
<p>The first step: know why you‚Äôre saving that link!</p>
<p>Then either spend up to 30 seconds writing why your future self will be interested in that material, or assign it up to two tags.</p>
<p>Everything you feel compelled to save for your future self to reference will fall under one of a repeating list of categories. Identify the ten (not 100) broadest of these and use them as tags.</p>
<p>Example categories:</p>
<ul>
<li>@person</li>
<li>relax</li>
<li>learn</li>
<li>project-a</li>
<li>project-b</li>
<li>buy</li>
<li>tech</li>
<li>recipe</li>
<li>try</li>
<li>blog</li>
</ul>
<p>Temporary tags may be needed if you are gathering material for a specific project.</p>
<h2 id="pick-an-app---or-not">Pick an app - or not</h2>
<p>The app you use really doesn‚Äôt matter. I like <a href="https://raindrop.io" target="_blank">Raindrop</a>, but I‚Äôm just as happy saving links to a plain text file and visiting the original source when I‚Äôm ready to start reading. It‚Äôs easy to add a Why sentence to Raindrop, but sometimes I share links to <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/157-2025-05-19-journelly-is-org-for-those-who-dont-do-org">Journelly</a> instead. It‚Äôs a good option when all you want is a link for reference purposes.</p>
<p>The Obsidian Web Clipper browser extension is a good way to save web pages into Markdown format for reading offline. Add a <code>why</code> property to your template, and/or use tags.</p>
<p>Now that Pocket has shut down, I‚Äôm seeing a lot of people moving to <a href="https://wallabag.it/en/" target="_blank">Wallabag</a>. It‚Äôs open source and is reasonably priced when you don‚Äôt want to self-host.</p>
<p>See also <a href="https://hookproductivity.com/blog/2025/07/10-great-mac-bookmarking-apps-and-services/" target="_blank">this post</a> on bookmarking services, from the creator of my favourite Mac utility of all time, Hookmark.</p>
<p>So. It‚Äôs now<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>later‚Äù, and you are settling down to read. You can still start at the top and scroll through, or you can zoom in with laser focus to the categories that interest you in that moment.</p>
<p>Filter out the work-related articles and enjoy those set aside for when you have time to relax, or vice versa.</p>
<h2 id="more-clarity-less-distraction">More clarity, less distraction</h2>
<p>We need more clarity, less distraction; more accessible resources, less clutter.</p>
<p>Attaching your Why to every link you save will help you build a body of reference material that will be easy to access, and even easier to delete without fear of losing something important.</p>
